purl("eir2pr.Rmd", output = "eir2pr.R", documentation = 0, quiet=TRUE)

-

A set of wrappers to compute the PfPR as a function of the PfEIR for any model.

  • steady – eir2pr_steady computes steady state values for the PfPR

  • orbit – eir2pr_orbit computes a one year orbit for the PfPR

In both models, we use Ztrace to pass a values of \(Z\) – the density of infective mosquitoes. We also set the parameters describing the overall blood feeding rate (\(f\)), and the human blood fraction (\(q\)). The daily EIR differs for every stratum: \[ \mbox{EIR} = \left(\beta \cdot fqZ \right) \frac{H}{\sum H}\] We choose values of \(Z\) such that the annual EIR varies in a mesh from \(0.1\) up to \(1,000\).

steady

Describe steady state relationships between PfEIR and the PfPR for a model.

-

Pseudocode

  • Set values of \(Z\) in Ztrace

    • We set \(Z\) but the EIR differs for every stratum. The population average EIR is \[ \left(\beta \cdot fqZ \right) \frac{H}{\sum H}\]

    • We want to output values of the annual EIR in a mesh from \(0.1\) up to \(1,000\), so we must first find values of \(Z\) such that aEIR \(=0.1\) & \(1,000\). We then take an even geometric mesh with nZvals

  • For each value of \(Z\), solve for the steady state of the system

  • Compute and store the population average PfPR and PfEIR

Output

  • PfEIR is returned in several forms:

    • a vector describing a range of values for the population average PfEIR

    • a matrix describing the PfEIR for each stratum

  • PfPR is returned in several forms:

    • PfPR_pop is the population average PfPR

    • PfPR_std is the average PfPR in children older than 2 but younger than 10 (for models defined ages)

    • PfPR_u5 is the average PfPR in children under 5 (for models defined ages)

    • PfPR is a matrix of steady state values for each stratum

Inputs

  • model is a fully parameterized model

  • nZvals

code

Z2eir = function(Z, model){
  model$MYZpar$Zm=Z
  H = F_H(0, 0, model)
  beta = F_beta(0, 0, model)
  eir = F_EIR(0, 0, model, beta)
  c(eir= sum(H*eir)/sum(H)) 
}
eir2Z = function(eir, model){
  df = function(Z, model){
    (eir - Z2eir(Z, model))^2
  }
  optimize(df, c(0, 10000), model=model)$min
}
eir2pr_Z = function(Z, model){
  model$MYZpar$Zm = Z
  y0 = get_inits(model)
  y = steady(y0, times = NULL, func=xDE_diffeqn_human, parms=model)$y
  H = F_H(0, 0, model)
  eir = Z2eir(Z, model)
  pfpr = y2pr_strata(y,model)
  c(aPfEIR=365*eir, PfPR=pfpr) 
}
eir2pr_steady = function(model, nZvals = 100){
  Zl = eir2Z(0.1/365, model)
  Zu = eir2Z(1000/365, model)
  Z = exp(seq(log(Zl), log(Zu), length.out = nZvals)) 
  t(sapply(Z, eir2pr_Z, model=model))
}

orbit

Describe stable orbits and for the PfEIR and the PfPR for a model with a defined seasonal pattern, and output the seasonal average values in a form that is directly comparable with steady state relationships.

-

Pseudocode

  • We define a mesh on \(Z\) as we did for eir2pr_steady

  • For each value of \(Z\), we find the stable orbit.

  • Compute and store the orbits and the population average PfPR and PfEIR

Output

  • PfEIR is returned in several forms:

    • a vector describing a range of values for the annual average PfEIR averaged across the population

    • a vector describing a range of values for the population average PfEIR across the year

    • a matrix describing the PfEIR for each stratum

  • PfPR is returned in several forms:

    • PfPR_pop is the population average PfPR

    • PfPR_std is the average PfPR in children older than 2 but younger than 10 (for models defined ages)

    • PfPR_u5 is the average PfPR in children under 5 (for models defined ages)

    • PfPR is a matrix of steady state values for each stratum

Inputs

  • model is a fully parameterized model

  • nZvals

code

reset_inits_X = function(model, y){
  UseMethod("reset_inits_X", model$Xpar)  
}

reset_inits_X.SIS = function(model, y){
  model$Xinits$X0 = y[model$Xpar$X_ix]
  return(model)
}

reset_inits_X.SIP = function(model, y){
  model$Xinits$X0 = y[model$Xpar$X_ix]
  model$Xinits$P0 = y[model$Xpar$P_ix]
  return(model)
}
Z2eir_season = function(Z, tt, model){
  tt = tt[-1]
  model$MYZpar$Zm=Z
  H = F_H(tt, 0, model)
  beta = F_beta(tt, 0, model)
  eir = sapply(tt, F_EIR, y=0, pars=model, beta=beta) 
  c(eir=sum(H*eir)/sum(H)/length(tt)) 
}
eir2Z_season = function(eir, tt, model){
  dfs = function(Z, tt, model, eir){
    (eir - Z2eir_season(Z, tt, model))^2
  }
  optimize(dfs, c(0, 10000), tt=tt, model=model, eir=eir)$min
}
eir2pr_Z_season = function(Z, model, nT){
  tt = seq(0,365, length.out = nT+1)
  model$MYZpar$Zm = Z
  y0 = get_inits(model)
  ode(y0, times = seq(0,7300, by = 10), func=xDE_diffeqn_human, parms=model) -> out
  y0 = tail(out, 1)[-1]
  model = reset_inits_X(model, y0)
  
  X = ode(y0, times = tt, func=xDE_diffeqn_human, parms=model)
  H = F_H(0, 0, model)
  Zs = F_Z(tt, 0, model)
  eirs = sapply(Zs, Z2eir, model=model) 
  pfpr = orbits2pr_strata(X,model)
  c(aPfEIR=365*eirs, PfPR=pfpr) 
}
eir2pr_season = function(model, nT = 24, nZvals = 100){
  tt = seq(0, 365, length.out = nT+1)
  Zl = eir2Z_season(0.1/365, tt, model)
  Zu = eir2Z_season(1000/365, tt, model)
  Z = exp(seq(log(Zl), log(Zu), length.out = nZvals)) 
  t(sapply(Z, eir2pr_Z_season, model=model, nT=nT))-> out
  aPfEIR = out[,1:(nT+1)]
  mean_eir = apply(aPfEIR, 1, mean)
  PfPR = out[,nT+1 + 1:(nT+1)]
  mean_pr = apply(PfPR, 1, mean)
  list(aPfEIR = aPfEIR, PfPR=PfPR, mean_pr=mean_pr, mean_eir=mean_eir)
}
